  "articleSummary": "The article argues that confusion around Postgres timestamp types stems from failing to distinguish between absolute moments (TIMESTAMPTZ), wall-clock times (TIME + timezone), and durations (INTERVAL). Using the metaphor of a train ticket showing departure, arrival, and travel time, it explains that TIMESTAMPTZ stores UTC-converted moments, not timezones, while TIMESTAMP stores naive local times. The tutorial-style piece targets developers building multi-region or scheduling systems, warning against exact timestamp equality due to microsecond precision mismatches with JavaScript, and recommends defaulting to TIMESTAMPTZ while storing context separately.",
